# what if you have additional stopwords to be removed
tokens = str(review)
#lowercase
tokens = tokens.lower()
# Remove useless numbers and alphanumerical words
tokens = re.sub("[^a-zA-Z0-9]", " ", tokens)
#tokenization or word split
tokens = word_tokenize(tokens)
#get stemming words or lemmas
wordnet_lemmatizer = WordNetLemmatizer()                             #Using Lemmatizer method.
tokens = (wordnet_lemmatizer.lemmatize(word) for word in tokens)
#additional stopwrods
more_stopwords = set(('cant', 'aint', 'today'))
extra_stoplist = set(stopwords.words('english')) | more_stopwords
tokens = (word for word in tokens if word not in extra_stoplist)
# Filter non-alphanumeric characters from tokens
tokens = (word for word in tokens if word.isalpha())
#remove short words
tokens = (word for word in tokens if len(word) >= 3)

# Example 3c: Elon Musk Speech 2017 with and without Stop Words 
from os import path
from wordcloud import WordCloud, STOPWORDS
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
%matplotlib inline


text = str(review)
text = text.replace("'", '')
text = text.replace(',', '')

# Take out some stopwords that are generic
stopwords = set(STOPWORDS)
stopwords.add("br")
stopwords.add("s")
stopwords.add("movie")
stopwords.add("film")
stopwords.add("films")
background_color="movies"



# Generate a word cloud image
wordcloud = WordCloud(background_color="white", max_words=2000).generate(text)

# Display the generated image:
# the matplotlib way:
plt.imshow(wordcloud)
plt.axis("off")

# take relative word frequencies into account, lower max_font_size
wordcloud = WordCloud(max_font_size=40, relative_scaling=.5, stopwords=stopwords).generate(text)
plt.figure(figsize=(10,10))
plt.imshow(wordcloud)
plt.axis("off")

#Example 4d: Cleaning Text
# remove extra brackets
reviews = [x for y in reviews for x in y]
# Remove useless numbers and alphanumerical words
documents = [re.sub("[^a-zA-Z]+", " ", document) for document in reviews]
# tokenize
texts = [[word for word in document.lower().split() ] for document in documents]
# remove common words 
stoplist = stopwords.words('english')
texts = [[word for word in text if word not in stoplist] for text in texts]
#remove short words
texts = [[ word for word in tokens if len(word) >= 3 ] for tokens in texts]

for row in texts[:5]:   
    data = str(row)
    data = data.replace("'", '')
    data = data.replace(',', '')
    score = sentiment(data)
    print(round(score[0],3), round(score[1],3))

# Example 1: Import NLTK and TextStat for Readability
# May needs to pip install textstat
# textstat is a Python package to calculate statistics from text 
# Determines readability, complexity and grade level of a particular corpus.
import nltk
import textstat
import pandas as pd
from nltk.tokenize import sent_tokenize, word_tokenize 
import re
import pandas as pd
from nltk.corpus import stopwords
import csv
In [129]:
# Example 13: Assess Readability of a Customer Service Tweets
# Example 13a: Get CSV File Contents (you many need to change the file path)
# Setup and Clear all lists in case
tweets = []
fleschre = []
smog = []
fleschkg = []
colemanliau = []
ari = []
dalchall = []
dw = []
linsearwrite = []
gunningfog = []
textstandard = []
tweets.clear()
textstandard.clear()
fleschre.clear()
smog.clear()
fleschkg.clear()
colemanliau.clear()
ari.clear()
dalchall.clear()
dw.clear()
linsearwrite.clear()
gunningfog.clear()

#openfile = open('data/sampledata_wordfrequency.csv', 'r', encoding = "ISO-8859-1")

openfile = open("/Users/rajivpuli/Desktop/McDonaldsCleaned copy.csv", "r", encoding = "ISO-8859-1")
r = csv.reader(openfile)

# Example 13b: Set idex value to -1 
j=-1



# Example 13c: Put all tweets into a list
for i in r:
    j=j+1
    tweets.append(i)
    
    # Example 13d: Find out if Tweet can be used with Smog Index (used tokenization this time)    
    number_sentences = len(sent_tokenize(str(tweets[j])))
                           
    if number_sentences < 3:
        # Put N/A into SMOG List for Tweet
        smog.append('N/A')
    else:
        # Put score into smog list for Tweet
        smog.append(textstat.smog_index(str(tweets[j])))
    
    # Example 13e: Put each Score into a list that corresponds to Tweets
    fleschre.append(textstat.flesch_reading_ease(str(tweets[j]))) 
    fleschkg.append(textstat.flesch_kincaid_grade(str(tweets[j])))
    colemanliau.append(textstat.coleman_liau_index(str(tweets[j])))
    ari.append(textstat.automated_readability_index(str(tweets[j])))
    dalchall.append(textstat.dale_chall_readability_score(str(tweets[j])))
    dw.append(textstat.difficult_words(str(tweets[j])))
    linsearwrite.append(textstat.linsear_write_formula(str(tweets[j])))
    gunningfog.append(textstat.gunning_fog(str(tweets[j])))
    
    # Example 13e: Check for invalid Composite scores
    if textstat.text_standard(str(tweets[j])) != '-1th and 0th grade': 
        textstandard.append(textstat.text_standard(str(tweets[j])))
    else:
        textstandard.append('N/A')

# Example 13f: All done so close csv file
openfile.close()

# Example 13c: Put all tweets into a list
for i in r:
    j=j+1
    tweets.append(i)
    
    # Example 13d: Find out if Tweet can be used with Smog Index (used tokenization this time)    
    number_sentences = len(sent_tokenize(str(tweets[j])))
                           
    if number_sentences < 3:
        # Put N/A into SMOG List for Tweet
        smog.append('N/A')
    else:
        # Put score into smog list for Tweet
        smog.append(textstat.smog_index(str(tweets[j])))
    
    # Example 13e: Put each Score into a list that corresponds to Tweets
    fleschre.append(textstat.flesch_reading_ease(str(tweets[j]))) 
    fleschkg.append(textstat.flesch_kincaid_grade(str(tweets[j])))
    colemanliau.append(textstat.coleman_liau_index(str(tweets[j])))
    ari.append(textstat.automated_readability_index(str(tweets[j])))
    dalchall.append(textstat.dale_chall_readability_score(str(tweets[j])))
    dw.append(textstat.difficult_words(str(tweets[j])))
    linsearwrite.append(textstat.linsear_write_formula(str(tweets[j])))
    gunningfog.append(textstat.gunning_fog(str(tweets[j])))
    
    # Example 13e: Check for invalid Composite scores
    if textstat.text_standard(str(tweets[j])) != '-1th and 0th grade': 
        textstandard.append(textstat.text_standard(str(tweets[j])))
    else:
        textstandard.append('N/A')

# Example 13f: All done so close csv file
openfile.close()

# Set up lists

positive_review = []
negative_review = []
neutral_review = []


analyzer = SentimentIntensityAnalyzer()

# Remove brackets - added....
reviews = [x for y in reviews for x in y]

# Remove the unwanted characters - Okay not to use this with VADER
#documents = [re.sub("[^a-zA-Z]+", " ", document) for document in reviews]

# Make lower - Okay not to use this with VADER
#texts = [[word for word in document.lower().split() ]for document in documents]


# Might be good not to use Data Frames right now.
#df = pd.DataFrame(reviews)
#df.columns = ['review']
#df.head(5)

#for sentence in documents:
#    vs=analyzer.polarity_scores(sentence)
#    df['compound'] = vs["compound"]
#df.head(5)

# Do what you did but this time put into array rather than dataframe
for sentence in reviews:
    vs = analyzer.polarity_scores(sentence)
    if (vs["compound"] > 0):
        positive_review.append(sentence)
    elif (vs["compound"] == 0):
        neutral_review.append(sentence)
    else:
        negative_review.append(sentence)
print(len(positive_review), 'positive reviews')
print(len(negative_review), 'negative reviews')
print(len(neutral_review), 'neutral reviews')
